## Key Design Principles

- **Real-time first**: Everything streams. The triage agent does not wait for a complete transcript — it acts on partial information and updates decisions as more context arrives.
- **Language-agnostic**: The caller can speak any language. Translation happens transparently before triage.
- **Multi-call awareness**: The RAG system means the agent gets smarter with every call and can correlate information across calls happening simultaneously.
- **Structured outputs**: All dispatch decisions and agency briefings should be structured/typed, not free-form text. Use Pydantic models for all agent outputs.
- **Latency matters**: This is a 911 system. Every architectural decision should minimize time-to-dispatch. Prefer streaming over batch processing everywhere.

## When Writing Code for This Project

- Always use **async/await** — the entire system is concurrent (multiple calls, streaming transcripts, parallel agents).
- Use **Pydantic** for all data models (call records, dispatch decisions, briefings).
- Prefer **streaming** LLM responses from Modal when possible.
- All Twilio webhook handlers should be non-blocking.
- Write code that handles partial/incomplete transcripts gracefully — the triage agent will receive incomplete sentences.
- Keep latency top of mind. If there is a faster way to do something, prefer it.
- This is a hackathon — prioritize working features over perfect abstractions. Ship fast, but keep the code readable for a 2-person team.

